TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Truck Dispatching Problem
AU  - Dantzig, G. B.
AU  - Ramser, J. H.
Y1  - 1959/10/01
PY  - 1959
DA  - 1959/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.6.1.80
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.6.1.80
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 80
EP  - 91
VL  - 6
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The paper is concerned with the optimum routing of a fleet of gasoline delivery trucks between a bulk terminal and a large number of service stations supplied by the terminal. The shortest routes between any two points in the system are given and a demand for one or several products is specified for a number of stations within the distribution system. It is desired to find a way to assign stations to trucks in such a manner that station demands are satisfied and total mileage covered by the fleet is a minimum A procedure based on a linear programming formulation is given for obtaining a near optimal solution. The calculations may be readily performed by hand or by an automatic digital computing machine. No practical applications of the method have been made as yet. A number of trial problems have been calculated, however.
AB  - The paper is concerned with the optimum routing of a fleet of gasoline delivery trucks between a bulk terminal and a large number of service stations supplied by the terminal. The shortest routes between any two points in the system are given and a demand for one or several products is specified for a number of stations within the distribution system. It is desired to find a way to assign stations to trucks in such a manner that station demands are satisfied and total mileage covered by the fleet is a minimum A procedure based on a linear programming formulation is given for obtaining a near optimal solution. The calculations may be readily performed by hand or by an automatic digital computing machine. No practical applications of the method have been made as yet. A number of trial problems have been calculated, however.
